(1583, 20, 'Interpreting the Civil Rights Movement', 'N', 2011, 57703, 'N', 'Lecture', 'Primarily for Undergraduates', 'Expository Writing', 15, '', '', 'According to civil rights scholar Charles Payne, "Our understanding of social change, our conceptions of leadership, our understanding of the possibilities of interracial cooperation are all affected by how we remember the movement." In this seminar, we investigate the work of remembering and interpreting the mid-twentieth-century civil rights movement. We consider both popular and scholarly accounts, and we focus on the use of speeches, memoirs, and newspapers to reconstruct the events of the past.', '', ''),
