(1629, 20, 'On Liberty', 'N', 2011, 55662, 'Y', 'Lecture', 'Primarily for Undergraduates', 'Expository Writing', 15, '', '', 'Students will examine competing conceptions of liberty in modern ethical and political thought, with particular attention to the conflict between "negative freedom" (non-interference) and "positive freedom" (self-determination), and employ these concepts in constructive reflection on contemporary politics.', '', ''),
