(1636, 20, 'Obsession', 'N', 2011, 15575, 'Y', 'Lecture', 'Primarily for Undergraduates', 'Expository Writing', 15, '', '', 'This course explores the cultural representation of obsession - in film, literature, and psychoanalytic case histories - asking how artistic accounts of aberrant emotions, compulsions, and habits might intersect with or diverge from scientific accounts of obsession and its potential manifestations. Under what conditions is obsession considered a virtue, and when does it become pathological? What can a study of obsession reveal about our conceptions of normality, attachment, perfectionism, and paranoia, and their place in contemporary society?', '', ''),
