(1661, 20, 'Lovesickness', 'N', 2011, 92438, 'Y', 'Lecture', 'Primarily for Undergraduates', 'Expository Writing', 15, '', '', 'This course examines the concept of love as an illness as it developed in literature and other disciplines from classical antiquity to the Renaissance to the present. Is lovesickness a scientific phenomenon or a poetic invention? From Plato, to Shakespeare, to Freud, and beyond, we will cover a wide range of works in literature, philosophy, and medicine to trace the changing vocabulary of lovesickness and its persistent role in contemporary culture.', '', ''),
